 affection for his subjects, and his keen-eyed ability to observe and record without prejudice stories, songs, and lore from everyone from death-row inmates to numbers runners, hustlers, and legendary blues musicians shines through. In his own words, Jackson's essays "bear witness" to worlds that others have too easily ignored. This book includes Jackson's landmark work on prison lore and toasts (the predecessor of rap); labor and criminology; his wide-ranging interest in African American lore and legend; his encounters with legendary figures including Alan Lomax and Pete Seeger; and articles that challenge the many traps and pitfalls that plague much of academic study. Folklore Matterswill delight, inform, and inspire all those who value America's deepest traditions and the endless creativity of the unrecognized masters of our national culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxFolklore. 0aFolk musiczUnited States. 0aFolklorexFieldworkzUnited States. 0aFolklorezUnited States. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Music. 4aLiterature : Folklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Folklore & Mythology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2024z978311149259940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849617740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438496177423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438496177/original  a978-3-11-149259-9  SUNY Press eBook Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles